data.content:
Yes! Modern MSTest (v3.3+) supports **tuple-based `DynamicData`**, giving you compile-time type safety without `object[]`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Key changes:**
- `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>` — the data source is now strongly typed
- Array literals `["...", true]` → tuple literals `("...", true)`
- Named tuple fields (`Input`, `Expected`) improve readability but are optional

This catches type mismatches at compile time rather than failing at runtime with a cast exception. Make sure you're on **MSTest 3.3+** (`Microsoft.Testing.Framework` / `MSTest.TestFramework` ≥ 3.3).
